{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d4e0635a-9ab8-4c9a-90d4-1a946e04e9d2","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — crash reports for your user\n- **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-wide crash reports\n\nLook for a file matching your process name with a `.ips` extension (e.g., `MyApp-2026-04-22-*.ips`).\n\n**Quick command to find it:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them in a GUI.\n\n> **Tip:** If you need a full memory dump (not just a crash report), you can configure `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `COMPlus_DbgMiniDumpName=/path/to/dump` before running the app — but for NativeAOT, the `.ips` crash log with its native backtrace is usually the starting point. Use the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill if you need help symbolicating the `.ips` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fe09e4d7-c607-4db4-89f2-27a81ec0311d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic question about .NET crash dumps. Let me check if the `dump-collect` skill is relevant here - it's described as \"Configure and collect crash dumps for modern .NET applications\" including NativeAOT.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"943C:135AB6:18FC036:1C53A48:69E81FDB"},"id":"564248bc-5e25-464c-af60-7dfdeb6fa004","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:09:57.865Z","parentId":"18a18e02-2003-478e-a9ee-13920b90f523"}
